<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1805,1974]" pageId="8" pageNumber="443">
North African 
<taxonomicName box="[317,468,1805,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphagidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="443" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Pamphaginae">Pamphaginae</taxonomicName>
have been studied by different orthopterists (e.g., Vosseler 
<number box="[1139,1198,1806,1830]" pageId="8" pageNumber="443" value="1903.0">1903</number>
, Bolivar 1907, 1908, 1912, 1914, Werner 1932, 1933, Chopard 
<number box="[629,687,1842,1866]" pageId="8" pageNumber="443" value="1943.0">1943</number>
, Uvarov 
<number box="[791,850,1842,1866]" pageId="8" pageNumber="443" value="1943.0">1943</number>
, Descamps 
<number box="[986,1045,1841,1866]" pageId="8" pageNumber="443" value="1968.0">1968</number>
, Descamps &amp; Mounassif 
<number box="[1335,1394,1842,1866]" pageId="8" pageNumber="443" value="1972.0">1972</number>
, La Greca 
<number box="[227,287,1878,1902]" pageId="8" pageNumber="443" value="1993.0">1993</number>
). Nearly all the species are squamipterous, character that has been almost lost in Asian species (it is maintained only in few Middle East genera, others are completely apterous). Thus, we may consider that squamipterous 
<taxonomicName box="[321,472,1949,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Pamphagidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="443" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Pamphaginae">Pamphaginae</taxonomicName>
should have evolved in North Africa.
</paragraph>
